    thickness = np.clip(np.random.normal(mean_target_thickness, np.sqrt(variance_target_thickness), q75_target_thickness) if np.random.rand() < 0.5 else np.clip(np.random.normal(q10_target_thickness, variance_target_thickness, median_target_thickness)
    pulse_width = np.clip(np.random.normal(mean_pulse_width, variance_pulse_width), q75_pulse_width if np.random.rand() < 0.6 else min_pulse_width, q10_pulse_width)

    spot_size = np.clip(np.random.normal(mean_spot_size, variance_spot_size), median_spot_size if np.random.rand() < 0.8 else q25_spot_size  # Again, bias towards the median and Q75
    intensity = np.clip(stats.norm.rvs(loc=mean_intensity, scale=np.sqrt(variance_intensity), size=1)[0] if np.random.rand() < 0.9 else stats.norm.rvs(loc=median_intensity, scale=np.sqrt(variance_intensity)/2, size=1)[0]  # Simplified approach to simulate the high variance in intensity
    power = np.clip(stats.norm.rvs(mean_power, variance_power, size=1)[0] if np.random.rand() < 0.9 else stats.norm.rvs(loc=median_power/2, scale=np.sqrt(variance_power)/2, size=1)[0]
    cutoff_energy = np.clip(stats.norm.rvs(mean_cutoff_energy, variance_cutoff_energy, q75_cutoff_energy if np.random.rand() < 0.9 else q25_cutoff_energy)
    
    # Randomly select the target material based on a simple categorical distribution for demonstration purposes; normally, this could be more complex or derived from data
    selected_material = np.random.choice(target_materials) if np.random.rand() < 0.8 else 'unknown'  # Simplified selection to introduce variability
    
    # Ensure power and cutoff_energy are within reasonable bounds based on the given statistics
    power = np.clip(power, min_power, max_power) if selected_material != 'unknown' else 0  # For 'unknown', we assume a minimal value or adjust accordingly
    cutoff_energy = np.clip(cutoff_energy, min_cutoff_energy, max_cutoff_energy)
    
    data_points.append([selected_material, thickness, pulse_width, energy, spot_size, intensity, power, cutoff_energy])

# Convert the list of lists to a numpy array for easier handling and visualization purposes
generated_data = np.array(data_points)
print(generated_data)
